production.title: Production
production.content: {{country}}'s plastic production industry is small but increasingly important to the domestic economy. About 5070 registered manufacturers, concentrated in Phnom Penh, Kandal, and the Sihanoukville SEZ, focus on secondary production, converting imported resins into packaging, containers, construction materials, and household goods. {{country}} does not produce base resins such as PE, PP, or PVC and relies on imports from e.g., China, Vietnam, and Thailand.

trade.title: Trade
keyTrends: {{country}} is a downstream plastics manufacturing hub, importing plastic materials and components, processes them, and re-exports them embedded in finished goods.

From 2017-2022, plastic imports nearly doubled while exports grew more than six-fold, but domestic plastic consumption fell, highlighting {{country}} is primarily a processing platform for export markets.

Imports are dominated by primary polymers, sheets, films, synthetic yarns and fabrics, while exports are almost entirely final products such as garments, footwear, packaging, and construction plastics.
{{country}} sources almost all plastic materials from Asia, while exporting finished goods mainly to the Americas and Europe.
Synthetic textiles drive the plastics economy in {{country}}, with industrial textiles providing inputs and predominantly driving finished apparel and footwear exports.
Most of the empty plastic packaging for domestic consumption is imported.
Concerning rubber, {{country}} exports raw natural rubber but imports processed rubber goods.
trade.summary:
Plastic trade trends

Between years 2017 and 2022, the amount of plastic imported to {{country}} has increased by 76.0%, while the amount of plastic exported from {{country}} has increased by 485.0 %.
trade.tradingPartners:
{{country}} sources almost all plastic materials from Asia. This reflects dependence on regional petrochemical producers (e.g., China, Thailand, and Vietnam) for resin, films, sheets, parts and components, and minimal reliance on Western or African suppliers.

{{country}} exports finished plastic goods primarily to high-income consumer markets, with the Americas and Europe acting as the largest buyers, followed by Asia as a secondary destination.
trade.productCategories: {{country}} predominantly imports textiles, apparel and footwear (HS chapters 54-65), particularly industrial textile inputs, with knitted fabrics (HS 6006 and 6004) accounting for over USD 2.8 billion. Top exports are almost entirely finished apparel and footwear, including jerseys, cardigans, dresses, trousers, T-shirts, footwear, babywear, and underwear. The second product category that dominates {{country}}'s plastic imports is plastics and articles thereof (HS Chapter 39), which covers raw materials, plastic packaging, construction-related plastic materials, plastic parts for various applications and a wide range of everyday plastic goods. Top import items in this category include sheets and films, primary polymers, packaging components, semi-finished plastic inputs, and industrial fittings. The third product category is rubber (HS Chapter 40), for which the largest import categories are synthetic rubber and blends, other vulcanised rubber articles, and new rubber tyres. Raw natural rubber and new rubber tyres dominate {{country}}'s exports in this category, although natural rubber is not a plastic product.
trade.summaryLeft:
Plastic Imports

A total of 15,312 million USD worth of plastic was imported to {{country}} between 2017-2022. In the latest reporting year 2022, the total imports reached value of 3,343 million USD, of which:

  • ~ 17% was plastic in primary forms
  • ~ 14% was plastic in intermediate forms
  • ~ 50% was intermediate manufactured plastic goods
  • ~ 19% was final manufactured plastic goods
  • ~ 0% was plastic waste.

The plastic imports included estimated 82 thousand tonnes (equivalent to 333 million USD) of plastic packaging imports with notoriously short product lifetime.

Plastic exports

A total of 7,557 million USD worth of plastic was exported from {{country}} in the year(s) 2017-2022. In the latest reporting year 2022, exports reached a value of USD 2,195 million, of which:

  • ~ 0% was plastic in primary forms
  • ~ 0% was plastic in intermediate forms
  • ~ 0% was intermediate manufactured plastic goods
  • ~ 99% was final manufactured plastic goods
  • ~ 0% was plastic waste.

Plastic exports included estimated 25 thousand tonnes of plastic packaging, equivalent to 53 million USD.

consumption.title: Consumption
consumption.content: Plastic consumption is calculated as total imports minus exports, using UNCTAD data. This data shows a decreasing trend in plastic consumption in {{country}}. Despite {{country}}'s significant growth in plastic imports and exports, domestic consumption of plastic peaked in 2018 and fell by about 25% by 2022. This indicates that {{country}} primarily imports plastics for re-export in manufactured goods.

wasteManagement.title: Waste Management
keyTrends: Plastic waste is increasing rapidly from municipal and industrial sources, particularly in urban, coastal and manufacturing hubs.
Plastic waste estimates vary widely (~297846 thousand tonnes per year), reflecting data uncertainty and the dominance of short-lived consumer and packaging plastics.

Waste collection and management are uneven, with ~54% of MSW collected nationally, with much lower coverage in rural areas. Uncollected waste is often incinerated or dumped, resulting in more than 400,000 tonnes of plastic emissions per year.
Landfilling predominates in formal disposal, whereas recycling remains minimal (~4%), largely limited to PET; most plastics are unrecovered.
Industrial growth adds pressure, with garments alone generating ~90 thousand tonnes per year of largely unmanaged waste.
wasteManagement.content:
Plastic waste from municipal solid waste

Estimates on annual municipal solid waste generation range from 1,225 to 4,780 thousand tonnes per year of municipal solid waste generated in {{country}} in 2020, with a generation rate ranging from 0.2 kg per person per day to 0.78 kg per person per day. Estimates on annual plastic waste generation range from 297 thousand tonnes per year to 846 thousand tonnes per year, depending on data sources and methodologies used for estimation.

A study on global waste management modelling showed 64% of municipal solid waste is collected, while another country-level study suggests waste collection rates are 91% in Phnom Penh but fall below 24% in rural areas.

The global waste management modelling showed that annual plastic emissions, including both debris and open burning, are 413,564 tonnes per year, equivalent to 25 kg/person/year. This is largely due to the uncollected waste and uncontrolled management of disposal facilities. An estimated percentage of municipal solid waste managed in controlled facilities is 4.8%. The estimated proportion of the MSW that is being recycled was 4% in year 2021.

The estimated MSW generation per capita in {{country}} in 2020 was 0.20 kg per person per day.
wasteManagement.contentRight:
Data from selected city case studies provide further insights into waste management in {{country}}. Primary data collection through a waste composition survey undertaken recorded that the share of plastic waste within the collected waste composition was 22% in Kep in 2021, and 32% in Sihanoukville in 2021. The same study primary data collection estimated that the per capita MSW generation in Kep was 1.20 kg and in Sihanoukville was 1.75 kg per person per day. In Phnom Penh Municipality, where about 39% of all {{country}}s waste is generated, plastic waste composition was reported to increase from 6% to 21% between 1999 and 2015. Plastic waste has been reported to constitute more than 20% of MSW in rural areas.

City case studies in Kep and Sihanoukville found that plastic waste recycled out of total plastic waste generated from municipal solid waste in Kep is 5%, and 8% in Sihanoukville in 2021. In both cities, PET dominates recycling, 0.28 t/day of PET out of 0.29 t/day recycled in Kep and 6.23 t/day of PET out of 8.5 t/day recycled. LDPE/films appear only marginally in recycling streams, and there is no recycling market for other types of plastic polymers.

Plastic waste from non-municipal solid waste

{{country}}s industrial sector has expanded rapidly, as trade data shows, driven by garments, construction, and manufacturing. While this growth supports economic development, it has significantly increased industrial waste, including textile offcuts, hazardous materials, construction debris, plastics, metals, and chemical residues, posing environmental and public health risks if poorly managed.

The garment industry dominates the sector. Calculations based on trade data have estimated that {{country}}s garment, footwear, and travel goods sector generated 136,151 tonnes of post-industrial textile waste between 2021 and 2022. Waste is commonly landfilled, downcycled, or burned in brick kilns. Other industries, such as food processing and construction materials, also contribute substantial waste streams.

environment.title: Plastics in the Environment
environment.content:
Mismanaged plastic waste escaping to the oceans and coasts

An estimated % of the escaped plastic from {{country}} ends up in the ocean and % ends up on the coasts. Mismanaged plastic waste is defined as plastic waste material that is either littered or inadequately disposed. Inadequately disposed waste is not formally managed and includes disposal in dumps or open, uncontrolled landfills, where it is not fully contained. These estimates are based on modelled data combining land-based sources of plastic debris and their modelled movements in the rivers and ocean. The plastic waste data are derived from global data on municipal solid waste.

The used studies estimate the amount of mismanaged waste as well as the part of this waste which enters the ocean, either directly or via rivers (or in other words, plastic waste that escapes to the environment). Mismanaged plastic waste from other countries also enters the ocean washing ashore to the coast of {{country}}. Estimated [No data] tonnes of plastic waste from the ocean reached {{country}} coast between [No data]. This plastic waste originated not only nationally, but also from other countries.

Beach litter

Plastic densities along coastlines are reportedly more than ten times the densities on river banks and more than twenty times that of inland areas. The total debris load along {{country}}s coastline is estimated at over 80 million items, with an average of 70,000 items per kilometre.

Water bottles, followed by other bottles, were the most common items found across coastal surveys, accounting for more than a quarter of all whole items. This was followed by thin-film carry bags and food wrappers. Polystyrene was the most common fragment type, followed by food container fragments, and fragments of string, rope, and ribbons.

sections.heading: Production and Trade
sections.text:
{{country}} is firmly positioned at the downstream end of the plastics value chain, importing plastic feedstocks and semi-manufactured inputs, especially synthetic textile materials, and re-exporting them embedded in finished apparel, footwear, and construction goods to high-income markets. {{country}}'s plastics industry plays a meaningful role in economic growth, and its position within global value chains gives it the potential to become a centre of innovation for circular design and sustainable plastic use at the manufacturing and packaging stages.

This model also generates substantial volumes of industrial plastic waste, including offcuts, rejects, and single-use flexible packaging (films, wraps, liners) used to protect goods during transport. These materials (often LDPE, PP, and mixed films) are low-value, rarely recycled, and prone to leakage, reinforcing national patterns in which flexible plastics dominate the waste stream and environmental emissions.

Strengthening industrial recycling incentives is therefore a critical pathway to improving overall recycling outcomes. Creating a reliable demand for recycled materials, particularly from textiles, apparel, footwear, and construction, would help transform currently low-value industrial waste into viable secondary resources.
policyOpportunities: Introduce eco-design and material standards for export-oriented manufacturing, prioritising mono-material, reduced polymer blends, and recyclability requirements for garments, footwear, and construction plastics, with explicit attention to eliminating unnecessary films and multi-layer packaging.

Embed plastic intensity and waste efficiency criteria into industrial investment incentives, rewarding manufacturers that minimise flexible packaging, offcuts, and rejects, and demonstrate on-site segregation and recovery of films and rigid plastics.

Implement extended producer responsibility (EPR) fees for major downstream users including international apparel brands and construction firms, with revenues earmarked for environmentally sound management of industrial plastic waste and the expansion of recycling infrastructure.

Use trade and industrial policy to catalyse local plastics recycling markets, including fiscal incentives for investments in domestic mechanical recycling of industrial textile and packaging waste, creating demand for materials that currently have little or no local value.

Leverage buyer and brand requirements in export markets to accelerate change, aligning national standards with international sustainability and circularity expectations, and shifting responsibility for problematic packaging upstream through supply-chain accountability systems.

sections.heading: Consumption
sections.text: Despite rising trade volumes, {{country}}'s apparent plastic consumption has declined since 2018, falling by about 25% by 2022. This suggests that the national plastic footprint is largely driven by foreign consumer demand rather than domestic use. However, local consumption patterns, especially single-use food and beverage packaging, are disproportionately responsible for visible litter and downstream pollution. Furthermore, (plastic) waste generation trends are also reported to have been increasing over the last decade.
policyOpportunities: Implement targeted restrictions or levies on high-leakage single-use plastics (e.g., beverage bottles, thin bags, food wrappers, polystyrene food containers) that dominate coastal and urban litter.
Introduce extended producer responsibility (EPR) for packaging, requiring importers and brand owners to finance collection and recycling of packaging placed on the {{country}}n market.
Promote reuse and refill systems in urban centres and tourist areas (e.g., water refill stations, reusable food container schemes), linked to tourism and hospitality standards.

sections.heading: Waste Management
sections.text: {{country}} generates an estimated 1.24.8 million tonnes of MSW annually, with per capita generation ranging from 0.2 to 0.78 kg per person per day, depending on location and methodology. Waste collection efficiency is estimated at up to 54%, with limited treatment options, leaving nearly half of MSW uncollected. Beyond MSW, rapid industrial growth, particularly in the garment and packaging sectors, has increased non-municipal plastic waste.
policyOpportunities: Prioritise rapid expansion of waste collection coverage and service reliability, particularly in peri-urban and rural districts where collection rates are lowest and open dumping and burning are most prevalent.
Establish a national plastic recovery target under extended producer responsibility (EPR), mandating phased increases in collection and recycling rates for plastic packaging.

Integrate the informal recycling sector into the formal system through licensing, buy-back centres and guaranteed offtake contracts, focusing initially on high-value PET bottles and rigid plastics, while laying the groundwork for future recovery of films and flexible packaging.
Improve control and monitoring of industrial plastic waste, particularly from textile, packaging, construction, and medical sectors, by expanding regulated disposal options outside major cities.
Invest in controlled disposal and treatment infrastructure, including regional landfills, transfer stations, and material recovery facilities.

sections.heading: Environment
sections.text: {{country}}'s coastlines are plastic pollution hotspots, with up to 70,000 litter items per kilometre, dominated by single-use beverage containers, thin bags, wrappers and polystyrene. Microplastics in the Mekong are primarily fibres and fragments, with concentrations increasing downstream, indicating that urban wastewater and poor waste containment are the primary leakage pathways.
policyOpportunities: Focus leakage prevention on high-impact items and hotspots, prioritising beverage packaging, thin bags and food containers in coastal provinces and major river corridors.
Upgrade waste containment and transfer infrastructure (covered bins, sealed trucks, storm-drain litter traps) in urban centres to cut direct leakage into waterways.
Require wastewater treatment upgrades in major cities to capture synthetic fibres and microplastics, paired with source-control measures in garment factories and laundries.
